'''Gerry Marks''' is a Canadian First Nations artist of [[Haida people|Haida]] ancestry.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Macnair|first1=Peter L.|last2=Hoover|first2=Alan L.|last3=Neary|first3=Kevin|title=The Legacy: Tradition and Innovation in Northwest Coast Indian Art|date=1984|publisher=Douglas & McIntyre|location=Vancouver, B.C.|isbn=978-0295961668}}</ref>

He grew up in [[Vancouver, British Columbia]], the grandson of John Marks, a Haida artist.

Marks studied with the Haida carver [[Freda Diesing]] in [[Prince Rupert, British Columbia|Prince Rupert, B.C.]], starting in 1971 and later studied at [[Hazelton, British Columbia|Hazelton, B.C.]]

In 1977 Marks and Francis Williams carved a 25-foot [[totem pole]] in [[Masset, British Columbia|Masset]], his ancestral Haida village on the [[Queen Charlotte Islands]].

