{{Infobox artwork | image_file = Waterhouse-sleep and his half-brother death-1874.jpg | title = Sleep and his Half-brother Death | artist = [[John William Waterhouse]] | year = 1874 | medium = [[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]] | material = | height_metric = 70 | width_metric = 91 | metric_unit = cm<!--don't leave this parameter blank—either don't include it, or include the default cm. Not including it will default it to cm.--> | city = | museum = | owner = }}
'''''Sleep and his Half-brother Death''''' is a painting by [[John William Waterhouse]] completed in 1874.<ref name="johnwilliamwaterhouse.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.johnwilliamwaterhouse.com/pictures/sleep-half-brother-death-1874/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090909160319/http://www.johnwilliamwaterhouse.com/pictures/sleep-half-brother-death-1874|dead-url=yes|archive-date=9 September 2009|title=Sleep and his Half-brother Death|publisher=johnwilliamwaterhouse.com|accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref>
Waterhouse's first [[Royal Academy]] exhibit (submitted from his father's house at 1 [[Scarsdale Villas]]),<ref name="Noakes">Noakes, Aubrey. 2004. ''Waterhouse: John William Waterhouse''. London: Chaucer Press. p. 23. {{ISBN|1-904449-39-5}}</ref> it was painted after both his younger brothers died of [[tuberculosis]].<ref name="Hobson">Hobson, Anthony. 1989. ''J. W. Waterhouse''. Oxford: Phaidon Christie's. pp. 20-21. {{ISBN|0-7148-8066-3}}</ref>
==Hypnos and Thanatos== The painting itself is a reference to the Greek gods [[Hypnos]] (sleep) and [[Thanatos]] (death) who, in the [[Greek mythology]], were brothers. Despite their similar poses in the painting, the character in the foreground is bathed in light, while his brother is shrouded in darkness; the first therefore represents Sleep, the latter Death.<ref name="Kryger2013">{{cite book|last=Kryger|first=Meir H. |title=Atlas of Clinical Sleep Medicine: Expert Consult - Online|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-bLVAQAAQBAJ&pg=PT61|year=2013|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-323-28917-7|page=61}}</ref> The personification of Sleep clasps poppies, symbolic of narcosis and dreamlike-states.<ref name="KrahnSilber2010">{{cite book|last1=Krahn|first1=Lois E.|last2=Silber|first2=Michael H.|last3=Morgenthaler|first3=Timothy I.|title=Atlas of Sleep Medicine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZaLSBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA5|date= 2010|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-84184-763-4|page=5}}</ref>
